# Docker

## Required

- All services run as a **non-root user** (`trader`, `api`, `nextjs`).
- Production images do not contain dev dependencies (separate dev/prod
  layers or `--no-dev` install).
- Each Dockerfile installs project deps, then copies code, then sets the
  user — in that order — so layer caching works.
- Python service images build from the shared local `trading-base` image.
  Build it with `docker build -f Dockerfile.base -t trading-base .` before
  service builds, or add an explicit CI/compose base-image step.
- Healthchecks are defined in `docker-compose.yml` for `redis`, `backend`,
  and `frontend`. The trading-engine container has a process-level liveness
  check via the orchestrator.
- The `trading-net` network is `external: true`. The host already runs
  `ollama` and `hermes` on it (see [`docs/INFRASTRUCTURE.md`](mdc:docs/INFRASTRUCTURE.md)).

## Windows Docker Desktop dev loop

When bind-mounting the repo on Windows/WSL2, never expose host-only dependency
or cache directories inside `/app`. `docker-compose.dev.yml` must mask:
`.venv`, `.git`, `.mypy_cache`, `.ruff_cache`, `.pytest_cache`, `.deepeval`,
`agent-transcripts`, `frontend/node_modules`, `frontend/.next`, and
`trading_lab.egg-info`.

Measured consequence from 2026-04-26: without masks, `/app` exposed ~3 GB and
pytest collection took 15+ minutes; with masks, `/app` was ~5.7 MB and the
inner-loop unit suite passed in ~53 seconds.

## Hostnames inside the network

Containers address each other by **service name**, never `localhost`:

| From → To           | URL                          |
|---------------------|------------------------------|
| frontend → backend  | `http://backend:8000`        |
| backend → redis     | `redis://redis:6379/0`       |
| any → ollama        | `http://ollama:11434`        |
| any → DuckDB volume | `/data/market.duckdb`        |

## Forbidden

- Running as root in production stages.
- Baking secrets into images. `.env` is mounted at runtime.
- Hard-coded `localhost` URLs in container code.
- Calling `docker compose up` from a hook (the user does this).
- Removing dev bind-mount masks without replacing them with an equivalent
  Windows-safe strategy.

## Build verification

Every Dockerfile change must be followed by:
```bash
docker compose build <service>
docker compose up -d <service> && docker compose logs --tail 50 <service>
```
CI builds all three images on every PR.
